@node "Main" "XPKGuide.Guide"
                                @{u}XPKGuide V1.9@{uu}

XPKGuide is an AmigaGuide viewer which can view AmigaGuide files which have
been crunched using @{"variousĀcrunchers" link "supported_crunchers" 0} (you can also view uncrunched files
using it).  You can either use it from the Shell or from Workbench.

There is also the added bonus that if you are using Workbench 3.x then
XPKGuide will also display any files which are supported by the
@{"datatypes.library" alink "SystemGuide/DataTypes.library" 0} including text files, pictures and samples. Naturally,
they will be decrunched before being viewed. Under Workbench 2.x you will
only be able to view AmigaGuide files and text files.

        @{"NoteĀaboutĀtheseĀdocs" link "NoteAboutDocs" 0}        @{"SystemĀRequirements" link "requirements" 0}
        @{"Installation" link "installation" 0}                 @{"SupportedĀCrunchers" link "supported_crunchers" 0}
        @{"UsageĀfromĀShell" link "usage_shell" 0}             @{"UsageĀfromĀWorkbench" link "usage_wb" 0}
        @{"History" link "history" 0}                      @{"Future" link "future" 0}
        @{"Copyright" link "copyright" 0}                    @{"Author" link "author" 0}
        @{"Known Bugs" link "bugs" 0}
@endnode

@node "NoteAboutDocs" "Note about this document file"
Whenever a name of a shared library appears in this document, it will be an
AmigaGuide button, these buttons will only work if you have Dan Elgaard's
@{"SystemGuide" link "about_systemguide" 0} somewhere in AmigaGuides path and as long as it is actually
called "@{"SystemGuide" link "about_systemguide" 0}".
@endnode

@node "requirements" "System Requirements"
XPKGuide requires Kickstart 2.04 or higher.

I've made a decision not to support Kickstart 1.3 any more, as I don't want
to support an obsolete operating system, everyone who uses their Amigas for
anything except games should have upgraded by now, as most programmers have
dropped support for Kickstart 1.3, and the ones who do still support it,
generally add extra features under Kickstart 2.

XPKGuide also requires the following library:

        @{"amigaguide.library" alink "SystemGuide/amigaguide.library" 0}      V34 or higher   (not supplied)


If you want to take advantage of XPKGuides localisation (when I finally
manage to write (or somebody else writes, hint hint) some more catalog
files), you need the following library:

        @{"locale.library" alink "SystemGuide/locale.library" 0}          V38+


If you want to be able to view files which have been crunched using
PowerPacker then you will need to have the following library installed:

        @{"powerpacker.library" alink "SystemGuide/powerpacker.library" 0}     V35 or higher   (supplied)


If you want to be able to view files which have been crunched using XPK
then you will need to have the following library installed:

        @{"xpkmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xpkmaster.library" 0}       any version     (supplied)


If you want to be able to view files which have been crunched using the
lh.library then you will need to have the following library installed:

        @{"lh.library" alink "SystemGuide/lh.library" 0}              V1 or higher    (supplied)


If you want to be able to view files which have been crunched using the
CrunchMania cruncher then you will need to have the following library
installed:

        @{"CrM.library" alink "SystemGuide/CrM.library" 0}             any version     (not supplied)


If you want to be able to decrunch files which have been crunched using a
cruncher which is supported by the @{"xfdmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xfdmaster.library" 0} then you need to have
the following library installed:

        @{"xfdmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xfdmaster.library" 0}       V33 or higher   (supplied)

Both CrunchMania and PowerPacker crunchers are supported by the @{"XFD" link "about_xfd" 0}
package, XPK is supported as of @{"XFD" link "about_xfd" 0} v1.02 as an external decruncher, but
PCompress and @{"lh.library" alink "SystemGuide/lh.library" 0} aren't supported by it. As an extra note, for the
@{"xfdmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xfdmaster.library" 0} to support XPK files, it needs the following files:
LIBS:xfd/XPK; LIBS:xpkmaster.library; and LIBS:Compressors/xpk????.library.
This means that XPKGuide will automatically use the @{"xpkmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xpkmaster.library" 0}
directly and not the @{"xfdmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xfdmaster.library" 0}.


If you don't have any of the above libraries, you will only be able to view
files which have been crunched using the P-Compress cruncher or files which
haven't been crunched at all.

The following library is optional and only needed if you want to be able to
double click XPKGuide from Workbench and get a file requester:

        @{"asl.library" alink "SystemGuide/asl.library" 0}             V37 or higher   (on Workbench disk)


The @{"amigaguide.library" alink "SystemGuide/amigaguide.library" 0} is needed to be able to display the decrunched
AmigaGuide files.

If you have Workbench 3.0 or higher then you already have the
@{"amigaguide.library" alink "SystemGuide/amigaguide.library" 0} installed on your Workbench disk and don't actually need
to install any other libraries before being able to use XPKGuide. If you
haven't got Workbench 3.0 or higher then you will need to get the
@{"amigaguide.library" alink "SystemGuide/amigaguide.library" 0} from somewhere else, the best place would probably be
from Fred Fish disk 920 which you can get from just about any PD library.

To be able to use XPKGuide to view crunched files, you must have T:
assigned somewhere, you don't need to worry about this is you haven't
altered you Startup-Sequence as everything is taken care of by that. You
may run into problems if T: is in RAM: (which it is normally) and you
haven't got that much memory, because the files are always decrunched into
T: and AmigaGuide files tend to be quite large. To get around this problem
you may need to assign T: to either a floppy disk or a hard disk.

By the way, if you're interested, the main reason that I don't just require
the @{"xfdmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xfdmaster.library" 0} and none of the other cruncher libraries is because
if you want to use XPKGuide as a viewer on a floppy disk system you could
just crunch all of your files using PowerPacker and just use the
@{"powerpacker.library" alink "SystemGuide/powerpacker.library" 0} (about 6K) rather than the @{"xfdmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xfdmaster.library" 0} (about
35K). Another reason is that I didn't want to waste all of the work which
I'd done already ;-)

If you think that XPKGuide is too large, then I'd recommend that you have a
look at MiniXpkGuide by Martin Gierich, it's only 488 bytes long so you
should be able to fit it onto almost any disk!
@endnode

@node "installation" "Installation"
In order to install XPKGuide you just drag the XPKGuide icon to whichever
drawer you want to keep it in. In order for XPKGuide to work you must have
some libraries installed, see Installation for details of which libraries
you need. You can install the libraries which I have supplied by double
clicking on the @{"InstallLibs" alink "InstallLibs.script/main" 0} icon which I have provided.
@endnode

@node "supported_crunchers" "Supported Crunchers"
At the moment XPKGuide supports the following crunchers:

        CrunchMania             To view CrunchMania files, you need to
                                have the @{"CrM.library" alink "SystemGuide/CrM.library" 0} installed.
        @{"lh.library" alink "SystemGuide/lh.library" 0}              (I mean that it supports files crunched
                                using LhEncode which was supplied with
                                the package on Fish Disk 436). Obviously
                                you need the @{"lh.library" alink "SystemGuide/lh.library" 0} installed to use
                                this.
        PowerPacker             To view files crunched using PowerPacker,
                                you need to have @{"powerpacker.library" alink "SystemGuide/powerpacker.library" 0} V35
                                or higher installed.
        Any XPK sublibrary      To view files crunched using XPK, you
                                must have both @{"xpkmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xpkmaster.library" 0} and
                                the appropriate compressor library
                                installed.

In addition to directly supporting the above crunchers, XPKGuide can also
use @{"XFD" link "about_xfd" 0} to decrunch a lot more types of crunched files.

I have also written another program called Cruncher which is designed to
complement XPKGuide, it is capable of crunching files using a number of
different crunchers including all of the above crunchers. I have also
written another program called AppDecrunch which can decrunch any files
which have been crunched by the above crunchers.
@endnode

@node "usage_shell" "Usage From Shell"
XPKGuide FILE/M,SCREEN/S,PUBSCREEN/K,QUIET/S,PORTNAME/K

If you don't enter any arguments then the asl.library file requester will
be opened if the asl.library is present to allow you to choose an
AmigaGuide file to view. Once you exit that, the requester will be brought
up again, this will continue until you select the Cancel gadget.

@{u}FILE/M@{uu}

This argument is compulsory. You are allowed to specify as many files as
you want, they will be displayed in the order that you enter them.

@{u}SCREEN/S@{uu}

If you specify this argument then XPKGuide will try to open a new screen to
display the AmigaGuide document on. If it can't open a new screen and the
PUBSCREEN argument has been given (see below) then XPKGuide will act as
though you didn't give the SCREEN argument. XPKGuide automatically tries to
open a screen with the same screen mode as your Workbench screen. This can
be changed by setting the @{"XPKGuide/ScreenModeĀenvironmentĀvariable" link "env_variables" 0}.

@{u}PUBSCREEN/K@{uu}

Using this you can specify which public screen you want XPKGuide to open
the AmigaGuide document on, if this screen isn't open and if the SCREEN
option was specified then XPKGuide will act as though the PUBSCREEN option
wasn't entered.

@{u}QUIET/S@{uu}

If you specify this option, XPKGuide won't display any information when it
is started.

@{u}PORTNAME/K@{uu}

Using this you can specify what the name of the ARexx port for this
document (or documents if you specified more than one) will be called.
@endnode

@node "usage_wb" "Usage from Workbench"
XPKGuide can be used in four ways from Workbench:

   XPKGuide can be specified as the default tool of a crunched AmigaGuide
file. This means that when you double click on the AmigaGuide file,
XPKGuide will be loaded and will display the AmigaGuide file.

   You can use extended selection to cause XPKGuide to view AmigaGuide
files. This means that you first click once on XPKGuide's icon and then
while holding down either shift key double clicking on an AmigaGuide file.
If you use extended selection to select more than one AmigaGuide file then
all of the files will be viewed, one at a time.

   If you just double click XPKGuide's icon then if the @{"asl.library" alink "SystemGuide/asl.library" 0} is
present then a file requester will be brought up for you to select a file
to view. If @{"asl.library" alink "SystemGuide/asl.library" 0} isn't present then an error message will be
displayed saying that no file was selected.

   You can tell XPKGuide to create an AppIcon when it's first loaded and
you are able to drop the AmigaGuide files onto it to view them. See below
for more details on this.

There are also a couple of tooltypes which are supported by XPKGuide. They
are:

        SCREEN
        PUBSCREEN=<pubscreen name>
        APPICON
        PORTNAME=<arexx portname>

   Both the SCREEN and PUBSCREEN tooltypes do exactly the same as the
@{"commandĀlineĀoptions" link "usage_shell" 0} of the same name.

   If the APPICON tooltype is specified then when you run XPKGuide without
specifying any files from Workbench then an AppIcon will be created and you
are able to drop any AmigaGuide files onto the AppIcon in order to view
them. If you drop more than one file onto the icon at the same time, all of
them will be viewed. Once you have created an AppIcon, if you double click
on it a requester will appear asking what you want to do, you can quit
XPKGuide, show some information about XPKGuide or cancel the requester.

   The PORTNAME tooltype tells XPKGuide what name to give the ARexx port
for this AmigaGuide document.
@endnode

@node "history" "XPKGuide Program History"
@{u}XPKGuide v1.9 (3 February 1995) ????? bytes@{uu}
   Added a Finnish catalog file for XPKGuide, many thanks to Heikki
Kantola.
   Removed support for PCompress crunched files, if you need to view these,
they are still handled via the xfdmaster.library.
   Due to the last change, XPKGuide is now pure again!
   Added a PORTNAME Shell option and tooltype.
   Fixed a couple of potential bugs concerning public screens.

@{u}XPKGuide v1.8 (13 January 1995) 16584 bytes@{uu}
   Fixed a bug when I tried to use the xfdmaster.library to view
PowerPacker files when powerpacker.library wasn't available that would
crash the computer.
   Also fixed a bug where XPKGuide wouldn't use xfdmaster.library to
decrunch any files, this was due to a difference between my own version of
the header files for it (used in v1.6) and the official header files (used
in v1.7 onwards).

@{u}XPKGuide v1.7 (11 January 1995) 16584 bytes@{uu}
   I'm now using Heddley to organise this AmigaGuide document.
   Slightly changed the method of linking with @{"SystemGuide" link "about_systemguide" 0}, I now tell the
@{"amigaguide.library" alink "SystemGuide/amigaguide.library" 0} to open a new window. The problem is that although this
works with v34 of the library, v39 doesn't support it, I don't know about
v40 though.
   I fixed a small bug with XPKGuides memory allocation while decrunching
files using the @{"CrM.library" alink "SystemGuide/CrM.library" 0}, you probably wouldn't loose any memory, but
who knows.
   Also now I don't use the MEMF_PUBLIC flag so XPKGuide should now be able
to make use of virtual memory if necessary while decrunching rather than
only using physical memory. I haven't got a MMU though so I can't test it.
   XPKGuide and XPKGuidePrefs have now both been localised, if anybody
wants to send me any new catalog files, they will be credited in the next
release, I've included some partial .ct files and a blank .ct file. I will
probably just upload a seperate archive with all the catalog files in.
   Removed some error messages and replaced them with a more general one.
   Fixed small bug where memory wouldn't get freed it decrunching a
CrunchMania file and XPKGuide couldn't open the temporary file.
   If you don't supply any parameters to XPKGuide when running it from the
Shell, the Asl file requester is brought up continually until you cancel
it.

@{u}XPKGuide v1.6 (9 December 1994) 14384 bytes@{uu}
   Slightly changed XPKGuide's method of opening the AmigaGuide file on a
public screen.
   Added a few more links in the documentation, so that if you click on a
libraries name and you have Dan Elgaard's @{"SystemGuide" link "about_systemguide" 0} installed on your
system then the relevant description will be loaded.
   Added support for the @{"xfdmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xfdmaster.library" 0}, so a lot more crunched files
can be viewed now!
   Added my Email address to this manual.

@{u}XPKGuide v1.5 (30 September 1994) 13400 bytes@{uu}
   Now recognises CrunchMania files without needing the @{"CrM.library" alink "SystemGuide/CrM.library" 0}
installed.
   XPKGuide now uses the LockE() command from the @{"amigaguide.library" alink "SystemGuide/amigaguide.library" 0}, this
allows XPKGuide to search for files by using the @{"AmigaGuide/Path" link "env_variables" 0}
environment variable. Although this worked for uncrunched files before this
version (without me realising!), it's only in this version I made XPKGuide
able to decrunch them after finding them in that way.
   XPKGuide now only opens the decruncher libraries which it needs, as it
needs them, instead of loading them all at startup.
   XPKGuide can now view files which have been crunched using P-Compress.
   Due to supporting the P-Compress cruncher, XPKGuide can no longer be
made resident.

@{u}XPKGuide v1.4 (3 September 1994) 11188 bytes@{uu}
   Added AppIcon support, including APPICON tooltype to tell XPKGuide to
create an AppIcon if no files were specified when run from Workbench.
   Can now view multiple documents using multiselect from Workbench.
   Can now view multiple documents from CLI.
   Fixed a few small bugs which caused a small amount of memory to be lost
each time you ran XPKGuide.
   Added support for files crunched using the @{"lh.library" alink "SystemGuide/lh.library" 0}.
   Added support for files crunched using CrunchMania (via the
@{"CrM.library" alink "SystemGuide/CrM.library" 0}).

@{u}XPKGuide v1.3 (21 August 1994) 7876 bytes@{uu}
   XPKGuide can now work as a stand-alone AmigaGuide viewer as both the
@{"powerpacker.library" alink "SystemGuide/powerpacker.library" 0} and the @{"xpkmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xpkmaster.library" 0} are now optional. They are
still needed in order to view crunched files though.
   XPKGuide now only creates a temporary file if the original was crunched
rather than for every file.

@{u}XPKGuide v1.2 (13 August 1994) 7608 bytes@{uu}
   Rewrote a few routines so they didn't use standard C routines, but
instead use my own versions. This saved 3172 bytes on XPKGuide and 3308
bytes on XPKGuidePrefs!
   I just discovered that, unknown to me, when you are using the Workbench
3.x version of @{"amigaguide.library" alink "SystemGuide/amigaguide.library" 0}, XPKGuide is able to display any type of
file which is supported by the @{"datatypes.library" alink "SystemGuide/datatypes.library" 0}. They will be decompressed
and viewed! This has happened since version 1.0, I just didn't realise it.

@{u}XPKGuide v1.1 (10 August 1994) 10880 bytes@{uu}
   Added more requesters to tell you what actually went wrong, rather than
just quitting and telling you nothing.
   Added a tooltype and command line option to allow XPKGuide to open the
AmigaGuide database on a separate screen. XPKGuide uses the Workbench's
current screen mode and size for the new screen.
   Also added another tooltype and command line option to allow XPKGuide to
open the AmigaGuide database on any public screen.
   XPKGuide now brings up the @{"ASL" alink "SystemGuide/asl.library" 0} file requester if you double click on its
icon.
   If you haven't got @{"xpkmaster.library" alink "SystemGuide/xpkmaster.library" 0} installed then XPKGuide tries to
use @{"powerpacker.library" alink "SystemGuide/powerpacker.library" 0} instead.
   Optionally uses an environmental variable to specify what screen mode to
open XPKGuide's custom window as.
   Added a tool which brings up a screen mode requester and sets the
@{"XPKGuide/ScreenMode" link "env_variables" 0} to the selected mode.

@{u}XPKGuide v1.0 (6 August 1994) 8232 bytes@{uu}
   Initial release
@endnode

@node "future" "Future"
@{u}Possible future additions to XPKGuide@{uu}
   Add more catalog files.
   This is almost definitely the last version of XPKGuide, over the summer
I'll probably start working on a replacement for MultiView (once I work out
how to use datatypes!)
@endnode

